  <!-- Level Descriptions -->
  <section class="section-pad">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Level 1 Condition Report - new builds and modern homes</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Level 1 surveys use a visual-only inspection method, examining accessible surfaces without moving furniture, lifting carpets, or testing services (RICS). The report assigns traffic-light condition ratings (green, amber, red) to each element but provides no repair advice, no cost estimates, and no valuation.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Level 1 suits new-build properties under 10 years old with an active NHBC warranty, where structural defects are covered by the warranty and the survey confirms the property matches its specification.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Cheshire new builds in Crewe (Gresty Oaks, Leighton West), Winsford (Weaver Park), and Northwich (Winnington Village) fall into this category. At £300 to £950, Level 1 is the lowest-cost option - but it misses defects that are not visible on the surface. For any property older than 10 years or any property without a structural warranty, Level 2 is the minimum appropriate level.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Level 2 HomeBuyer Report - standard Cheshire properties</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Level 2 surveys inspect all accessible areas of the property interior and exterior, including roof spaces where a hatch exists, and provide condition ratings with repair advice for each defect identified (RICS). The surveyor uses a damp meter on internal walls, checks for visible signs of movement or subsidence, and assesses the general condition of services (heating, electrics, plumbing) without testing them. An optional market valuation upgrade adds a comparison to recent local sales.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Level 2 covers the majority of Cheshire purchases: post-1960 detached and semi-detached homes in Wilmslow, Macclesfield, Frodsham, and suburban Chester. At £400 to £1,000 depending on property value, Level 2 provides enough detail for standard construction methods (cavity walls, pitched tile roofs, concrete foundations) while flagging anything that requires further specialist investigation. The report identifies issues but does not quantify repair costs - that requires Level 3 or a specialist follow-up.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Level 3 Building Survey - period properties and listed buildings</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Level 3 surveys provide a comprehensive structural analysis covering all accessible and visible elements, with detailed descriptions of construction methods, materials, defects, and their causes (RICS). The surveyor tests timber for rot, examines pointing and mortar condition, checks drainage runs, inspects cellars and sub-floor spaces, and provides repair cost estimates for every defect. The report runs 30 to 50 pages and takes 4 to 8 hours of on-site inspection.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Level 3 is necessary for Chester's sandstone townhouses (lime mortar joints, lead flashing, stone erosion), Nantwich's timber-framed buildings (wattle-and-daub panels, oak frame movement, beetle damage), and any listed building where repairs require Conservation Area or Historic England approval.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Golden Triangle period homes in Knutsford, Alderley Edge, and Prestbury with pre-1914 construction also warrant Level 3. At £600 to £1,500+, the survey costs more than Level 2 but provides repair cost estimates needed to renegotiate the purchase price with precision.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

