  <!-- Town Descriptions -->
  <section class="section-pad" style="background-color: #FFFFFF; border-top: 1px solid #E5E0D8; border-bottom: 1px solid #E5E0D8;">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Chester - sandstone, medieval, and Georgian townhouses</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Chester's city centre properties use red sandstone construction spanning Roman foundations through Georgian facades to Victorian commercial buildings. Sandstone absorbs moisture at 12-15% by volume (British Geological Survey), causing surface erosion, salt crystallisation damage, and lime mortar joint decay. A Level 3 survey in Chester examines stone weathering depth, pointing condition, lead flashing integrity around chimney stacks, and cellar damp - features absent from a standard Level 2 checklist.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Chester's Rows - the medieval two-level shopping galleries unique to the city - present additional surveying complexity where residential accommodation sits above or behind commercial frontages. Conservation Area restrictions in central Chester require any remedial work identified by the survey to use historically appropriate materials and methods, increasing repair costs by 20-40% compared to standard construction (Chester Civic Trust).</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Nantwich - timber-framed buildings from the 15th to 17th century</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Nantwich contains over 150 listed buildings, the highest concentration in Cheshire, with timber-framed construction dating from the 1400s to the 1600s (Historic England). The Great Fire of Nantwich in 1583 destroyed much of the town - surviving pre-fire buildings and the rebuilding wave that followed produce a housing stock where oak frames, wattle-and-daub infill panels, and lime plaster finishes require specialist surveyor knowledge.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Level 3 surveys on Nantwich timber frames assess frame deflection (the amount the oak structure has moved from its original position over centuries), death watch beetle and common furniture beetle infestation in structural timbers, and moisture readings in wattle-and-daub panels.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">A generalist surveyor flags "timber frame movement" as a defect; a specialist surveyor distinguishes between historic settlement (stable) and active movement (requiring intervention). Instructing a surveyor with timber-frame experience in the Nantwich market reduces the risk of unnecessarily alarming findings.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Knutsford and Wilmslow - period character homes and luxury estates</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Knutsford's housing stock mixes Victorian and Edwardian properties along King Street and Toft Road with 1930s semis and modern infill developments. Properties averaging £480,000 to £618,694 (Rightmove, 2026) frequently feature solid-wall construction, original slate roofs, and period features that a Level 2 survey assesses adequately for post-1900 buildings. Pre-1900 properties or those with visible signs of movement warrant Level 3.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Wilmslow ranges from 1960s detached homes on established residential roads (Level 2 appropriate) to substantial period properties and modern luxury builds exceeding £1,000,000. The higher property values in both towns increase surveyor fees proportionally - a Level 2 at Wilmslow's £550,000 average costs £650 to £850 compared to £400 to £500 at Crewe's £185,000 average. Properties with swimming pools, extensive grounds, or self-contained annexes require the surveyor to assess additional structures, extending both time and cost.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Macclesfield - Victorian terraces and renovation prospects</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Macclesfield's silk mill heritage produced dense rows of Victorian stone terraces in the town centre, with post-war and modern estates on the outskirts. Stone terraces at the £250,000 to £350,000 range present specific survey concerns: shared party walls where pointing deterioration in one property affects the neighbour, rear extensions built without modern building regulation compliance, and shared drainage systems where blockages are a joint responsibility.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Level 2 covers most Macclesfield properties. Victorian terraces with visible cracking or recent renovations benefit from Level 3 to assess whether structural changes followed proper engineering specifications.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Crewe, Northwich, and Winsford - post-war and modern housing</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Crewe's housing stock centres on post-war semi-detached and terraced properties (1950s-1970s) alongside modern new-build estates from the 2010s onwards. New builds under NHBC warranty need a Level 1 or snagging survey only. Post-war properties at Crewe's £185,000 to £197,000 average need Level 2 to check for cavity wall tie corrosion (common in 1960s-1980s construction), flat roof deterioration on extensions, and asbestos in textured coatings and soffits.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Northwich and Winsford carry brine subsidence as a primary survey risk, elevated above every other Cheshire town. Northwich sits directly above the Cheshire salt field where historical wild brine pumping caused extensive ground collapse - the town was partially rebuilt in the early 1900s using transportable timber-framed buildings designed to be moved when the ground shifted.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">A Level 2 survey in Northwich or Winsford must include specific subsidence assessment, and the mandatory Cheshire Salt Search (£79) provides the historical mining data the surveyor needs to evaluate ground stability risk at the specific property address.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Cheshire-Specific Issues -->
  <section id="cheshire-issues" class="section-pad">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <span class="section-label">Cheshire survey risks</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">What Cheshire-specific issues do surveys uncover?</h2>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Cheshire surveyors prioritise different defects depending on which part of the county the property sits in. A Chester inspection focuses on sandstone moisture absorption and lime mortar integrity. A Northwich survey centres on ground stability and brine void proximity. A Frodsham report checks radon accumulation readings against the 200 Bq/m3 action level. The sections below cover each risk, its geographic concentration, and the cost to remediate.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Condensation and damp in older Cheshire properties</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Damp is the most common defect Cheshire surveyors report, appearing in 60-70% of pre-1960 property surveys (RICS). Cheshire's boulder clay subsoil retains moisture, and older properties built with solid walls (no cavity) absorb ground moisture through capillary action - rising damp. Chester's sandstone properties are particularly susceptible because sandstone's porosity (12-15% moisture absorption) draws water upward and through walls more readily than brick.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Condensation damp results from inadequate ventilation in properties where original fireplaces and airbricks have been sealed during renovation. Victorian and Edwardian homes in Macclesfield, Knutsford, and Chester frequently show black mould at window reveals and external wall corners - a ventilation issue, not a structural defect, but one that costs £200 to £2,000 to resolve depending on whether the fix requires mechanical ventilation or simply reopening sealed vents.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">The surveyor distinguishes between rising damp (requires a damp proof course - £2,000 to £5,000), penetrating damp (requires external repair - £500 to £3,000), and condensation (requires ventilation improvement - £200 to £2,000).</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Brine subsidence and the mandatory Cheshire Salt Search</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">The Cheshire Salt Search is a mandatory conveyancing search for any property within the Cheshire Brine Compensation District, costing £79 inc VAT (Law Society). The search reveals whether the property sits above historical salt mining workings, active brine extraction zones, or areas where ground subsidence has been recorded.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Northwich, Winsford, and Middlewich carry the highest subsidence risk because wild brine pumping - injecting water underground to dissolve rock salt, then extracting the brine - created underground voids that collapsed unpredictably from the 1800s through to the mid-1900s.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">The Cheshire Brine Subsidence Compensation Board compensates property owners for damage caused by historical salt mining under the Brine Pumping (Compensation for Subsidence) Act 1891, amended 1952. Compensation covers repair costs, and where damage renders the property beyond economic repair, the Board pays the market value as a commutation payment.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">The Winsford rock salt mine - the largest and oldest active salt mine in the UK, operating since 1844 - continues controlled extraction at depth, but modern mining techniques produce minimal surface subsidence compared to the historical wild brine pumping.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">A property survey in Northwich or Winsford checks for subsidence indicators: stepped cracking in brickwork, doors and windows that stick or have been re-hung, sloping floors, and gaps between walls and ceilings. The salt search result and the survey findings together determine whether a lender approves the mortgage without additional conditions. Properties with active subsidence or unresolved compensation claims are difficult to mortgage - the survey provides the evidence the lender requires.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Radon risk in western Cheshire</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Radon is a naturally occurring radioactive gas that accumulates in enclosed spaces, particularly ground-floor rooms and cellars, where it enters through cracks in floors and walls (UK Health Security Agency). Western Cheshire wards - including parts of Chester, Frodsham, and the Delamere Forest area - sit on geological formations that produce above-average radon levels.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">A radon test costs £30 to £50 and takes three months of monitoring with a passive detector. Properties in radon-affected areas require mitigation (a radon sump or positive pressure ventilation, £800 to £1,500) if readings exceed the 200 Bq/m3 action level. Level 2 and Level 3 surveys note radon risk areas and recommend testing, but the survey itself does not measure radon - that requires a separate test kit from the UKHSA.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Renegotiation -->
  <section id="renegotiation" class="section-pad" style="background-color: #FFFFFF; border-top: 1px solid #E5E0D8; border-bottom: 1px solid #E5E0D8;">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <span class="section-label">Renegotiation evidence</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Can a survey save you money on a Cheshire property?</h2>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>85% of property surveys identify at least one defect requiring attention, and the average buyer renegotiates £8,000 off the purchase price based on survey findings</strong> (RICS, 2025; Compare My Move, 2025). On a £350,000 Knutsford property with a Level 2 survey costing £500 to £700, an £8,000 renegotiation produces a return of 11 to 16 times the survey fee.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The renegotiation is strongest when the survey quantifies repair costs. Level 3 reports include cost estimates - "roof re-slating: £8,000 to £12,000" gives the buyer a concrete figure to present to the seller. Level 2 reports identify defects without costings, requiring the buyer to obtain separate repair quotes before renegotiating. Both approaches work, but Level 3 accelerates the renegotiation because the evidence is already in one document.</p>

      <div style="border: 1px solid #E5E0D8; padding: 24px; margin-bottom: 24px;">
        <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; color: #3D5A3E; margin: 0 0 16px 0; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Survey ROI at three Cheshire price points</p>
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 8px;">
          <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; padding: 8px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #F0EDE8;">
            <span style="color: #444444;">£185,000 Crewe - Level 2 (£450)</span>
            <span style="color: #1C1C1E; font-weight: 600;">0.24% of price</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; padding: 8px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #F0EDE8;">
            <span style="color: #444444;">£350,000 Knutsford - Level 2 (£600)</span>
            <span style="color: #1C1C1E; font-weight: 600;">0.17% of price</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; padding: 8px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #F0EDE8;">
            <span style="color: #444444;">£750,000 Alderley Edge - Level 3 (£1,350)</span>
            <span style="color: #1C1C1E; font-weight: 600;">0.18% of price</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; padding: 12px 0 0 0;">
            <span style="color: #1C1C1E; font-weight: 700;">Average renegotiation saving</span>
            <span style="color: #C4933F; font-weight: 700; font-size: 18px;">£8,000</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; color: #999999; margin: 16px 0 0 0;">Survey cost as percentage of purchase price. Average renegotiation saving source: Compare My Move, 2025.</p>
      </div>

      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Cheshire-specific findings strengthen the renegotiation position further. A subsidence flag in Northwich, rising damp in a Chester sandstone property, or a timber beetle report in a Nantwich building creates repair liabilities that sellers recognise as legitimate price reduction grounds. Sellers in competitive Cheshire areas (Knutsford, Wilmslow, Alderley Edge) accept price reductions rather than risk the buyer withdrawing - remarketing a property after a failed sale adds 4 to 8 weeks and signals issues to subsequent buyers.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">The 15% of surveys that find no significant issues provide their own value: confidence that the property is structurally sound and fairly priced. Proceeding without a survey saves £400 to £1,500 upfront but removes the only independent assessment of the property's condition before committing to a purchase that typically exceeds £200,000 in Cheshire.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
  <section id="faq" class="section-pad">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 800px;">
      <span class="section-label">Survey questions</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Survey questions for Cheshire buyers</h2>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Cheshire buyers ask these property survey questions about new builds, timing, finding a local RICS surveyor, and what to do when the survey identifies problems.</p>
      <div>
        {faqs.map((faq, index) => (
          <details style={`border-top: ${index === 0 ? '2px solid #3D5A3E' : '1px solid #E5E0D8'};`}>
            <summary style="padding: 20px 0; cursor: pointer; font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 600; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.4; list-style: none; display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; gap: 16px;">
              {faq.question}
              <span style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; color: #C4933F; flex-shrink: 0;">+</span>
            </summary>
            <div style="padding-bottom: 24px;">
              <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">{faq.answer}</p>
            </div>
          </details>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Callout -->
  <section class="section-pad" style="border-top: 1px solid #E5E0D8;">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <div style="border-left: 3px solid #C4933F; background-color: rgba(196, 147, 63, 0.04); padding: 24px 28px;">
        <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; color: #C4933F; margin: 0 0 8px 0; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Why skipping a survey costs more than commissioning one</p>
        <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">
          A Level 2 survey on a £300,000 Macclesfield property costs £450 to £650 - between 0.15% and 0.22% of the purchase price. The average renegotiation saving from survey findings is £8,000 (Compare My Move, 2025). Undiscovered defects after completion become the buyer's sole financial responsibility, with no recourse to the seller under English property law's caveat emptor principle.
        </p>
        <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: #444444; margin: 0;">
          Roof replacement costs £5,000 to £15,000. Subsidence underpinning costs £10,000 to £50,000. Damp proof course installation costs £2,000 to £5,000. A survey identifies these before exchange of contracts - the last point at which the buyer can renegotiate, request repairs, or withdraw without losing the deposit.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related Spokes -->
  <section class="section-pad" style="border-top: 1px solid #E5E0D8;">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">Buying guide</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 28px 0;">Related Cheshire buying guides</h2>
      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(260px, 1fr)); gap: 20px;">
        {relatedSpokes.map((spoke) => (
          <a href={spoke.href} class="pillar-card" style="text-decoration: none; display: block;">
            <span style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: #3D5A3E; margin-bottom: 10px; display: block;">{spoke.tag}</span>
            <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 600; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0; line-height: 1.4;">{spoke.label}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script>
    const ageSelect = document.getElementById('survey-age') as HTMLSelectElement;
    const areaSelect = document.getElementById('survey-area') as HTMLSelectElement;
    const priceInput = document.getElementById('survey-price') as HTMLInputElement;
    const calcBtn = document.getElementById('survey-calc-btn') as HTMLButtonElement;
    const resultDiv = document.getElementById('survey-result') as HTMLElement;
    const levelResult = document.getElementById('survey-level-result') as HTMLElement;
    const costResult = document.getElementById('survey-cost-result') as HTMLElement;
    const notesEl = document.getElementById('survey-notes') as HTMLElement;
    const roiEl = document.getElementById('survey-roi') as HTMLElement;

    // Format input with commas
    priceInput.addEventListener('input', () => {
      const raw = priceInput.value.replace(/[^0-9]/g, '');
      if (raw) {
        priceInput.value = parseInt(raw).toLocaleString('en-GB');
      }
    });

    interface AreaInfo {
      notes: string[];
      pushLevel3: boolean;
    }

    const areaData: Record<string, AreaInfo> = {
      chester: { notes: ['Sandstone construction requires specialist mortar and stone assessment', 'Conservation Area restrictions increase repair costs by 20-40%'], pushLevel3: true },
      nantwich: { notes: ['Timber frame specialist surveyor recommended', 'Listed building consent required for most repairs', 'Death watch beetle and furniture beetle inspection critical'], pushLevel3: true },
      knutsford: { notes: ['Solid-wall construction common in Victorian/Edwardian stock', 'Slate roof condition a priority check'], pushLevel3: false },
      wilmslow: { notes: ['Cavity wall tie corrosion common in 1960s-1980s properties', 'Check flat roof sections on rear extensions'], pushLevel3: false },
      macclesfield: { notes: ['Victorian stone terraces - check shared party wall condition', 'Rear extension building regulation compliance'], pushLevel3: false },
      crewe: { notes: ['NHBC warranty check on new builds', 'Cavity insulation defects on 1970s stock'], pushLevel3: false },
      northwich: { notes: ['High brine subsidence risk zone', 'Salt Search mandatory (£79)', 'Ground stability assessment essential', 'Check for stepped cracking and door/window alignment'], pushLevel3: false },
      winsford: { notes: ['Active salt mine proximity', 'Salt Search mandatory (£79)', 'Ground stability assessment on older properties'], pushLevel3: false },
      frodsham: { notes: ['Sandstone damp absorption in older properties', 'Radon risk in western wards - testing recommended (£30-£50)'], pushLevel3: false },
      alderley: { notes: ['Complex roof structures on large detached properties', 'Basement and cellar damp assessment', 'Annexe and outbuilding compliance check'], pushLevel3: false },
      prestbury: { notes: ['Extensive grounds drainage assessment', 'Outbuilding structural integrity', 'Historical extension compatibility check'], pushLevel3: false },
      other: { notes: ['Salt Search mandatory within the Brine Compensation District (£79)'], pushLevel3: false },
    };

    function getLevel(age: string, area: string): { level: string; levelNum: number } {
      const areaInfo = areaData[area] || areaData.other;

      if (age === 'listed') return { level: 'Level 3', levelNum: 3 };
      if (age === 'period') return { level: 'Level 3', levelNum: 3 };
      if (age === 'victorian' && areaInfo.pushLevel3) return { level: 'Level 3', levelNum: 3 };
      if (age === 'victorian') return { level: 'Level 2 or 3', levelNum: 2.5 };
      if (age === 'postwar' && areaInfo.pushLevel3) return { level: 'Level 2 or 3', levelNum: 2.5 };
      if (age === 'postwar') return { level: 'Level 2', levelNum: 2 };
      if (age === 'modern') return { level: 'Level 2', levelNum: 2 };
      if (age === 'new') return { level: 'Level 1', levelNum: 1 };
      return { level: 'Level 2', levelNum: 2 };
    }

    function getCostRange(levelNum: number, price: number): string {
      if (levelNum <= 1) return '£300-£500';
      if (levelNum <= 2) {
        if (price <= 200000) return '£400-£500';
        if (price <= 300000) return '£450-£650';
        if (price <= 400000) return '£500-£750';
        if (price <= 550000) return '£650-£850';
        if (price <= 800000) return '£800-£1,000';
        return '£900-£1,000';
      }
      if (levelNum <= 2.5) {
        if (price <= 200000) return '£400-£750';
        if (price <= 300000) return '£450-£850';
        if (price <= 400000) return '£550-£1,050';
        if (price <= 550000) return '£650-£1,200';
        if (price <= 800000) return '£800-£1,500';
        return '£900-£1,800';
      }
      // Level 3
      if (price <= 200000) return '£630-£750';
      if (price <= 300000) return '£700-£900';
      if (price <= 400000) return '£850-£1,050';
      if (price <= 550000) return '£950-£1,200';
      if (price <= 800000) return '£1,200-£1,500';
      return '£1,400-£1,800';
    }

    function formatMoney(n: number): string {
      return '£' + n.toLocaleString('en-GB');
    }

    calcBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const age = ageSelect.value;
      const area = areaSelect.value;
      const price = parseInt(priceInput.value.replace(/[^0-9]/g, ''));

      if (!age || !area || !price || price < 0) return;

      const { level, levelNum } = getLevel(age, area);
      const costRange = getCostRange(levelNum, price);
      const areaInfo = areaData[area] || areaData.other;

      levelResult.textContent = level;
      costResult.textContent = costRange;

      // Build notes
      const notes: string[] = [...areaInfo.notes];
      if (age === 'listed') notes.unshift('Listed building - Historic England or Conservation Officer approval required for repairs');
      if (age === 'new') notes.unshift('Check NHBC warranty coverage and expiry date');

      notesEl.innerHTML = notes.map(note =>
        `<div style="display: flex; gap: 8px; font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; padding: 6px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #F0EDE8;">
          <span style="color: #3D5A3E; font-weight: 600; flex-shrink: 0;">-</span>
          <span style="color: #444444;">${note}</span>
        </div>`
      ).join('');

      // ROI line
      const midCost = levelNum <= 1 ? 400 : levelNum <= 2 ? (price <= 300000 ? 550 : price <= 550000 ? 750 : 950) : (price <= 300000 ? 800 : price <= 550000 ? 1075 : 1450);
      const costPct = ((midCost / price) * 100).toFixed(2);
      roiEl.textContent = `Survey costs approximately ${costPct}% of purchase price (${formatMoney(midCost)} midpoint). Average saving from renegotiation: £8,000.`;

      resultDiv.style.display = 'block';
    });
  </script>
</BaseLayout>
